\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 H/Paracleitus - knowledge is impossible because everything is in a state of flux - never step in the same river twice}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Parmenides -knowledge is divinely revealed through the fundamental being - being does not change because then it would no longer be being. Change is an illusion. We are in being and being is static.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 - first true analytical metaphysician;}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 But this contradicts our senses. We don\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92t experience a world which is unchanged or static.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 This produces a trifecta of problems.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 1.)are things constantly changing, or are they not?}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 2.)If things are changing what can be known about them, if anything. If not, is the knowledge that there is being simplicitor trivial or not?}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 3.)What are we to do with this in terms of values. If being is all there is and everything around me is a persistent delusion.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Socrates doesn\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92t care about all this. For him its all about socratic questioning and how to live a good life.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Plato\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s \u8216\'91solution\u8217\'92 is to posit two worlds. World of being which is unchanging and static. Therefore, true things can be known about it. There is also a parallel world, of becoming; things are constantly changing, but nothing can be known about this world. THe human being are the nexus of these two worlds. Body with sesnses; but with a soul that remembers the forms, is able to recognise them in the world, in the things in the world of becoming which participate in the forms.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 But where did the forms in the realm of being come from. If they are eternal, what are they? Where did the souls come from? Why are the souls enmeshed in matter? How did we get here?}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 In the timaeus, plato gave a story to explain the existence of all of this. He never calls it a myth, but a \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8216\'91likely story\u8217\'92. Here we have a primeval demiurge whose emergence is unclear. The demiurge looks upon the forms and attempts to press them into matter. There is imperfection.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Agrapha dogmata- the unwritten doctrines of plato - thorny subject.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 7th letter of plato - report of aristozenus - }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Plato\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s critiques of writing - truth cannot be captured in it.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Doctrine of the forms is not in the academy at this point. Scucipus rejects it. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Through diairesis (division in reality) we come to learn the truth. THis is the purpose of life. Preparation for death.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 \hich\f1 \emdash \loch\f1 underneath the hood of platonism is pythogoras - very geomterical}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 What was the Academy? }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 380s. Just after the disaster at syracuse. Plato attempted to teach a tyrant philosophy. Went badly wrong. Plato was sold into slavery and had to be redeemed by Leon. Plato returns to atens and establishes the academy.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Named after a hero of old - hacademos or academos}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Shrines to the muses and the graces}
