\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 According to Cobb, "process theology may refer to all forms of theology that emphasize event, occurrence, or\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Becoming_(philosophy)"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\i0 b}}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul\ulc0\cf4 ecoming}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \~over\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Being"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\i0 s}}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul\ulc0\cf4 ubstance}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 . In this sense theology influenced by\~}{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Georg_Wilhelm_Friedrich_Hegel"}{\fldrslt\f0\fs24\b0\i0 G}}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul\ulc0\cf4 . W. F. Hegel}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \~is process theology just as much as that influenced by Whitehead.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Modern theologians reject the classical-theist claim that }{\f3\fs24\b0\i1 God has no real relations to creatures}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  because they believe it makes God too metaphysically distant, undermines divine love, collapses biblical language, and is incompatible with modern philosophical commitments about personhood and relationality.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 If God had real relations, He would change. If God changed, He would not be God.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Modern theology says:}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 If God cannot have real relations, He cannot love. If God cannot love, He is not the God of Scripture.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 This is the fundamental divide.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb210\ltrch\loch {\f2\fs28\b1\i0 <$Scr_H::3>Wayne Grudem<!$Scr_H::3>}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls2\ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 God is immutable in His being.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s relationships change because creatures change.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 These relational changes do not imply change in God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s nature.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb210\ltrch\loch {\f2\fs28\b1\i0 <$Scr_H::3>Millard Erickson<!$Scr_H::3>}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls3\ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Advocates \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93qualified immutability.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s character is constant, but His actions vary.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s relational changes are expressions of His eternal nature.}
\par\pard\plain \fi720\sl288\slmult1\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 But when we get down to the bottom and actually analyze propositions of these forms of god, the become incoherent.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f2\fs24\b1\i0 Evangelicals say:}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls4\ilvl0{\listtext	\f2\fs24\b1\i0 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f2\fs24\b1\i0 God is affected}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	\f2\fs24\b1\i0 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f2\fs24\b1\i0 but God does not change}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f2\fs24\b1\i0 Process theologians argue this is contradictory. To be affected }{\f4\fs24\b1\i1 is}{\f2\fs24\b1\i0  to change.}
\par\plain \f2\fs24\b1\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Process theologians say this collapses relationality into determinism:}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls5\ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 If God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s responses are eternally fixed, they are not real responses.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 If God\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s relational acts are eternally decreed, they are not relational.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Thus evangelicals affirm relationality in language but deny it in metaphysics.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93To be affected is to change.\u8221\'94}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls6\ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Evangelicals end up with a God who is \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93immutable in essence but mutable in relation,\u8221\'94 which Hasker says is }{\f2\fs24\b1\i0 metaphysically impossible}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 .}
\par\pard\plain \fi720\sl288\slmult1\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The key here is that we are in relation to the essence. If we change, and then he changes in response, then we relation changes in accordance with the way HE has changed. He is no longer the ground of being.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls7\ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 If God is timeless, He cannot respond.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 If God responds, He is not timeless.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Evangelicals who affirm both timelessness and relational responsiveness hold an }{\f2\fs24\b1\i0 inconsistent set of propositions}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 .}
\par\pard\plain \fi720\sl288\slmult1\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls8\ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 God cannot be immutable in all respects and still have }{\f2\fs24\b1\i0 knowledge of tensed facts}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0  (\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93now,\u8221\'94 \u8220\'93today,\u8221\'94 \u8220\'93tomorrow\u8221\'94).}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Evangelical attempts to distinguish \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93essential\u8221\'94 vs. \u8220\'93relational\u8221\'94 change fail because }{\f2\fs24\b1\i0 knowledge is an essential property}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 .}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0 swinburne}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 We wish to avoid relativity, in which nothing can be known because nothing can be measured, there is no standard. You have no identity except in relation to something else.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Why do we need a grounding to being??}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Deriving meaning?}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0 Ground-of-being models regard ultimate reality as holy or sacred (unlike subordinate-deity models) and reject the idea that ultimate reality is an aware, agential being (unlike agential-being models). Ground-of-being models are radically anti-anthropomorphic, resisting the Intentionality Attribution, Narrative Comprehensibility, and Rational Practicality dimensions of anthropomorphism simultaneously. They are strongly amenable to the scientific study of religion and to apophatic metaphysical frameworks, within which ultimate reality surpasses the complete cognitive grasp of any possible creature. They offer a compelling and natural solution to the problem of religious diversity. They are and have always been relatively less popular than agential-being and subordinate-deity ultimacy models but it is not impossible to imagine a civilizational transformation after which ground-of-being models would become the dominant religious outlook. Variations, strengths, and weaknesses of the ground-of-being class of ultimacy models are discussed.}{ }
\par\plain 
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {A }{\f0\fs24\b1 ground\_of\_being}{ model becomes necessary when you want an account of ultimate reality that is:}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls9\ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b1 non\_anthropomorphic}{ (avoids projecting human traits onto the ultimate)}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b1 compatible with science}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b1 capable of explaining religious diversity}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b1 not committed to a personal God}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b1 still able to preserve the sacred or holy dimension of ultimacy}
\par\pard\plain \fi720\sl288\slmult1\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b1
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {Ground\_of\_being models avoid:}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls10\ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{exclusivism}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{revelation\_based epistemology}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{anthropomorphic bias}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{moral problems of divine agency (e.g., theodicy)}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{metaphysical problems of divine action}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {They simply sidestep the entire cluster of issues}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 Paul Tillich was critical of the view of God as a type of being or presence. He felt that, if God were a being, God could not then properly be called the source of all being (due to the question of what, in turn, created God). As an alternative, he suggested that God be understood as the \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93ground of Being-Itself\u8221\'94.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 He felt that, since one cannot deny that there is being (where we and our world exist), there is therefore a Power of Being. He saw God as the ground upon which all beings exist. As such, God precedes \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93being itself\u8221\'94 and God is manifested in the structure of beings.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0 To give contrast to the common image of God as presence/being, he used the term \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93God Above God\u8221\'94.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\plain {Many analytic philosophers argue the question is not even well\_formed.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb210\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs28\b1 <$Scr_H::3>A. \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Nothing\u8221\'94 is not a possible state of affairs<!$Scr_H::3>}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {This is the Carnap/Wittgenstein line:}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls11\ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Nothing\u8221\'94 is not a thing.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{It cannot be the subject of a question.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{Asking \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Why is there something rather than nothing?\u8221\'94 treats \u8220\'93nothing\u8221\'94 as a possible world, but it isn\u8217\'92t one.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b1 Argument:}{ To ask \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Why is there something?\u8221\'94 presupposes that \u8220\'93nothing\u8221\'94 is a coherent alternative. But \u8220\'93nothing\u8221\'94 cannot be described without smuggling in existence (e.g., the concept of nothingness, the laws of logic, the possibility of worlds).}
\par\plain {Thus the question collapses into nonsense.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb210\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs28\b1 <$Scr_H::3>B. Category mistake<!$Scr_H::3>}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {Gilbert Ryle\endash style argument: The question treats \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93existence itself\u8221\'94 as a thing that could have a cause. But existence is not a member of the category \u8220\'93things that have causes.\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {It\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s like asking:}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls12\ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93What color is the number 7?\u8221\'94}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Where is the hole when the donut is eaten?\u8221\'94}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb210\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs28\b1 <$Scr_H::3>C. Linguistic confusion<!$Scr_H::3>}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {Some philosophers argue the question arises from misuse of quantifiers:}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls13\ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Why are there any entities at all?\u8221\'94 But quantification presupposes a domain. You cannot quantify over a domain that does not exist.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {Thus the question is grammatically seductive but semantically empty.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb270\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs48\b1 <$Scr_H::1>\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u55358\'3F\u56809\'3F 2. The question might be }{\f0\fs48\b1\i1 coherent but unanswerable<!$Scr_H::1>}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {This is a more modest position.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb210\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs28\b1 <$Scr_H::3>A. We lack the conceptual tools<!$Scr_H::3>}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {Thomas Nagel and Derek Parfit suggest the question is intelligible but beyond human cognitive capacity. We can ask it, but we cannot answer it.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb210\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs28\b1 <$Scr_H::3>B. Explanatory regress<!$Scr_H::3>}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {Any answer seems to require a deeper explanation:}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls14\ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{If the universe exists because of laws \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8594\'3F why do the laws exist?}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{If the universe exists because of a necessary being \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8594\'3F why does the necessary being exist?}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{If the universe exists because of a brute fact \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8594\'3F why that brute fact rather than another?}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {Every explanation seems to generate a new \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93why.\u8221\'94}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb210\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs28\b1 <$Scr_H::3>C. Modal limitations<!$Scr_H::3>}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {Some philosophers argue we cannot meaningfully compare:}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls15\ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{the actual world}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{the \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93null world\u8221\'94 (a world with no objects, no laws, no space, no time)}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {Because the null world is not a world at all.}
\par\plain {Thus the question is coherent but cannot be answered within modal logic.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb270\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs48\b1 <$Scr_H::1>\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u55358\'3F\u56809\'3F 3. The question might be meaningful and answerable<!$Scr_H::1>}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {This is the minority view but includes major figures.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb210\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs28\b1 <$Scr_H::3>A. The universe exists because non\_existence is impossible<!$Scr_H::3>}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {Peter van Inwagen argues that \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93nothingness\u8221\'94 is not a metaphysically possible state. Thus the universe exists necessarily.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb210\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs28\b1 <$Scr_H::3>B. The universe exists because something is more probable than nothing<!$Scr_H::3>}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {Derek Parfit (in another mood) suggests that \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93something\u8221\'94 is more likely than \u8220\'93nothing\u8221\'94 because there are more possible worlds with something than with nothing.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb210\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs28\b1 <$Scr_H::3>C. The universe exists because of a necessary entity or principle<!$Scr_H::3>}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {Some analytic metaphysicians (Swinburne, Pruss, Koons) argue:}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls16\ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{There must be a necessary being or necessary law.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{That necessary entity explains why anything exists.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {This is a modernized version of Leibniz\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s answer.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb210\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs28\b1 <$Scr_H::3>D. The universe exists because of a brute fact<!$Scr_H::3>}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {Some naturalists (e.g., Quentin Smith) argue:}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls17\ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{The universe exists for no reason.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{Existence is a brute fact.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{The question has an answer: \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93There is no answer.\u8221\'94}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {This is a legitimate metaphysical position.}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb270\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs48\b1 <$Scr_H::1>\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u55358\'3F\u56809\'3F 4. Why the debate is so difficult<!$Scr_H::1>}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {Contemporary analytic philosophers disagree because the question touches multiple domains:}
\par\pard\plain \li540\fi-270\sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \ls18\ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b1 Semantics}{ \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0  what does \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93nothing\u8221\'94 mean?}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b1 Modal logic}{ \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0  is \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93nothing\u8221\'94 a possible world?}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b1 Metaphysics}{ \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0  can existence have a cause?}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b1 Epistemology}{ \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0  can humans grasp ultimate explanations?}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b1 Philosophy of language}{ \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0  is the question grammatically misleading?}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext	 \uc0\u8226 	}{\f0\fs24\b1 Philosophy of science}{ \hich\f0 \emdash \loch\f0  does physics allow \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93nothing\u8221\'94?}
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch {The question sits at the intersection of all these, and each field gives a different answer.}
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0
\par\plain 
\par\plain 
\par\pard\plain \sa180\sb180\ltrch\loch \f0\fs24\b0\i0
\par\plain \f0\fs24\b0\i0}